01:02:54.146 --> 01:02:57.106
that there's going to be an invading horde

01:02:57.190 --> 01:03:00.860
come from either the city
or from someplace unknown

01:03:00.944 --> 01:03:04.071
to savage their suburban community.

01:03:04.156 --> 01:03:07.908
To me, not only is it bizarre,

01:03:07.993 --> 01:03:11.120
but it's totally unfounded.

01:03:11.204 --> 01:03:14.081
And these pistols, curiously enough,

01:03:14.166 --> 01:03:16.750
weren't being taken off of kids
in the city of Flint,

01:03:16.835 --> 01:03:19.962
but were being taken off of kids
out in the out-county area

01:03:20.046 --> 01:03:23.257
in the suburban communities.

01:03:23.341 --> 01:03:26.010
-And –
-I didn't think that's what you were gonna say.

01:03:26.094 --> 01:03:29.472
I thought you were gonna say
it's all these black kids in inner city schools

01:03:29.556 --> 01:03:31.056
that had these guns.

01:03:31.141 --> 01:03:33.559
No. That's –

01:03:33.643 --> 01:03:38.147
We've never really had many problems
with guns in the city.

01:03:38.231 --> 01:03:41.066
Not to say we haven't. We've had some.

01:03:41.151 --> 01:03:42.860
But that's never been the biggest problem.

01:03:42.944 --> 01:03:45.571
The biggest problem
has been the gun possession

01:03:45.655 --> 01:03:49.074
by these adolescents in suburbia.

01:03:50.619 --> 01:03:52.536
- How'd you get a gun?
- I stole mine.

01:03:52.621 --> 01:03:54.914
-Where'd you steal it from?
-I stole it from a friend of mine.

01:03:54.998 --> 01:03:56.916
-Where'd he get it?
-His dad owns a bunch of guns.

01:03:57.000 --> 01:04:00.294
-What were you doing with the stolen guns?
-We went down to Detroit to try to sell 'em.

01:04:01.004 --> 01:04:03.631
'Cause I can get a buck-fifty a pop
for a nine millimeter.

01:04:03.715 --> 01:04:05.424
- Really?
- Yeah.

01:04:05.509 --> 01:04:08.219
-Who were you trying to sell them to?
-Anybody that would really want 'em.

01:04:08.303 --> 01:04:10.596
Mostly gangs and stuff like that.

01:04:10.680 --> 01:04:12.181
-Gangs in the city of Detroit?
-Yeah.

01:04:12.265 --> 01:04:14.350
- Black?
- Predominantly.

01:04:14.434 --> 01:04:15.809
-Yeah?
-Yeah.

01:04:15.894 --> 01:04:18.938
-So now you're okay?
-Yeah, I'm free now. I'm completely clear.

01:04:19.022 --> 01:04:21.982
-You can keep selling guns?
-Well, I can't really keep selling guns.

01:04:22.067 --> 01:04:24.527
It's getting too risky, man.
Everybody knows me up here.

01:04:24.611 --> 01:04:27.321
People want guns, or drugs, or alcohol,
they come to my house.

01:04:27.405 --> 01:04:30.866
-And that's just too much.
-Yeah, too much hassle.

01:04:32.827 --> 01:04:35.913
My favorite statistic in all the research I did

01:04:35.997 --> 01:04:39.875
discovered that the murder rate
had gone down by 20 percent.

01:04:39.960 --> 01:04:41.335
The coverage –

01:04:41.419 --> 01:04:45.047
that is, how many murders
are on the evening news –

01:04:45.131 --> 01:04:47.258
went up by 600 percent.

01:04:47.342 --> 01:04:54.056
The American people are conditioned
by network TV, by local news,

01:04:54.140 --> 01:04:56.183
to believe that their communities

01:04:56.268 --> 01:04:58.978
are much more dangerous
than they actually are.

01:04:59.062 --> 01:05:01.272
For example, here in this community,

01:05:01.356 --> 01:05:04.984
crime has decreased every year
for the past eight years.

01:05:05.068 --> 01:05:09.238
Yet gun ownership, particularly
handgun ownership, is on the increase.

01:05:09.322 --> 01:05:12.449
Crime rates have been dropping,
dropping, dropping.

01:05:12.534 --> 01:05:15.452
Fear of crime has been going up, up, up.

01:05:15.537 --> 01:05:17.955
How can that be possible?
It doesn't make any sense.

01:05:18.039 --> 01:05:22.209
But it makes perfect sense when you see
what we're hearing from politicians

01:05:22.294 --> 01:05:24.503
and seeing in the news media.

01:05:24.588 --> 01:05:29.300
So we're right here on the corner
of Florence and Normandie.

01:05:29.384 --> 01:05:32.595
This was kind of ground zero for the LA riots.

01:05:32.679 --> 01:05:34.513
Right.

01:05:34.598 --> 01:05:38.017
If a couple of white guys go down
and walk around South Central,

01:05:38.101 --> 01:05:39.476
they're gonna get killed,

01:05:39.561 --> 01:05:41.395
which I can tell you is a common perception.

01:05:41.479 --> 01:05:46.150
The odds that something's going
to happen to us are really, really slight.

01:05:46.234 --> 01:05:47.985
-Minuscule.
-Right. Okay.

01:05:48.069 --> 01:05:51.822
But, you know, if you look up there,
you get a different symbol

01:05:51.906 --> 01:05:53.490
of the Hollywood sign.

01:05:53.575 --> 01:05:56.577
It means something very different
than the corner of Florence and Normandie

01:05:56.661 --> 01:05:58.621
for most Americans and most of the world.

01:05:58.705 --> 01:06:00.998
It means glamour and Hollywood,
except that we can't see it.

01:06:01.082 --> 01:06:03.917
I can't see the Hollywood sign.
Where is it?

01:06:04.002 --> 01:06:06.337
You can't see it because of something

01:06:06.421 --> 01:06:09.632
that's probably
much more dangerous for us right now,

01:06:09.716 --> 01:06:11.342
which is the stuff we're breathing.

01:06:11.426 --> 01:06:14.136
The pollution that's blocking the Hollywood sign,
we're breathing this.

01:06:14.220 --> 01:06:18.932
That's far more dangerous than all the other stuff
the media's telling us to be afraid of.

01:06:19.017 --> 01:06:22.144
As we left the corner
of Florence and Normandie,

01:06:22.228 --> 01:06:26.065
I noticed that a number of helicopters
had appeared in the sky.

01:06:26.149 --> 01:06:29.443
Within seconds,
the news media started to arrive.

01:06:29.527 --> 01:06:32.488
- So what's the story here?
- I'm waiting. I thought you would know.

01:06:32.572 --> 01:06:34.406
No, I don't know anything.

01:06:34.491 --> 01:06:37.951
A sergeant told me it's a guy with a gun,
but they're not sure.

01:06:38.036 --> 01:06:39.912
-That's all they told me.
-All right.

01:06:39.996 --> 01:06:41.664
Since no action,
I'm not getting the camera down.

01:06:41.748 --> 01:06:44.249
I just happened to see the chopper.
We were going to another story.

01:06:44.334 --> 01:06:46.293
-What story you going to?
-It's a near drowning.

01:06:46.378 --> 01:06:48.337
-It's a drowning?
-Near drowning.

01:06:48.421 --> 01:06:51.548
How about the story about how
you can't see the Hollywood Hills

01:06:51.633 --> 01:06:53.717
because of the pollution?

01:06:53.802 --> 01:06:55.886
Could you maybe
do a story on that tonight?

01:06:55.970 --> 01:06:58.931
Pollution. You probably could.
I probably could.

01:06:59.015 --> 01:07:01.016
You can't see it.
You can't see anything around here.

01:07:01.101 --> 01:07:04.478
If you have to choose between a guy with a gun
and a near drowning of a baby,

01:07:04.562 --> 01:07:06.355
and you can only be in one place
at one time –

01:07:06.439 --> 01:07:08.107
-Go with the gun.
-You go with the gun always.

01:07:08.191 --> 01:07:09.483
-Go with the gun.
-Yeah.

01:07:09.567 --> 01:07:11.443
Is it all over here?

01:07:11.528 --> 01:07:13.278
All over? All over?

01:07:13.363 --> 01:07:15.114
-Not yet. Not yet.
-Looks like it.

01:07:15.198 --> 01:07:19.493
Just wait for these sergeants down here
to come down 'cause they got all the details.

01:07:19.577 --> 01:07:22.996
Okay. Hey, I was just wondering,
I just got here to LA today.

01:07:23.081 --> 01:07:26.834
I can't see the Hollywood sign
down on the hills there, down Normandie.

01:07:26.918 --> 01:07:28.919
-I can't see the sign 'cause of the pollution.
-Right.

01:07:29.003 --> 01:07:33.048
Is there anybody you can go and arrest
for polluting up the air?

01:07:33.133 --> 01:07:34.800
-Absolutely not.
-Nobody?

01:07:34.884 --> 01:07:36.969
-No.
-Why's that?

01:07:38.763 --> 01:07:40.681
Why is that, Sergeant?

01:07:47.188 --> 01:07:47.354
He's fighting him.

01:07:47.355 --> 01:07:48.814
He's fighting him.

01:07:49.774 --> 01:07:54.027
For over a decade, there has been
one show on American television

01:07:54.112 --> 01:07:56.572
that has consistently brought
black and white people together

01:07:56.656 --> 01:08:00.534
in an effort to reduce our fears
and celebrate our diversity.

01:08:00.618 --> 01:08:02.035
Get that hand back here.

01:08:02.120 --> 01:08:04.079
That show is Cops.

01:08:07.417 --> 01:08:10.335
I went to see a former producer of Cops

01:08:10.420 --> 01:08:13.130
and executive producer
of World's Wildest Police Videos,

01:08:13.214 --> 01:08:14.923
Mr. Dick Herlan.

01:08:15.008 --> 01:08:18.426
Look "liberal" up in the dictionary,
and my picture's in there somewhere.

01:08:18.511 --> 01:08:20.636
- Yeah.
- So then –

01:08:21.389 --> 01:08:24.640
You know,
why not be compelled to do a show

01:08:24.725 --> 01:08:28.604
that focuses on what's causing the crime,

01:08:28.688 --> 01:08:31.023
as opposed to just
chasing the criminals down?

01:08:31.107 --> 01:08:33.649
Because I think
it's harder to do that show.

01:08:33.734 --> 01:08:35.944
I don't know what that show would be.

01:08:36.029 --> 01:08:38.988
Anger does well. Hate does well.
Violence does well.

01:08:39.073 --> 01:08:40.448
Tolerance and understanding

01:08:40.533 --> 01:08:43.786
and trying to learn to be a little different
than you were last year does less well.

01:08:43.870 --> 01:08:45.453
- Does less well in the ratings.
- Yeah.

01:08:45.537 --> 01:08:48.290
Maybe because we,
in the television business,

01:08:48.374 --> 01:08:52.836
because we tend to demonize
black and Hispanic people,

01:08:52.921 --> 01:08:56.423
then those watching it at home are going,
"I don't want to help those people.

01:08:56.508 --> 01:08:58.884
I'm not going to do anything to help them
because I hate them now,

01:08:58.968 --> 01:09:00.886
because they may hurt me."

01:09:00.970 --> 01:09:02.720
You know what I'm saying?

01:09:02.805 --> 01:09:05.808
I know what you're saying.
I'm not sure that's what we're doing.

01:09:06.684 --> 01:09:13.607
I'm not sure we're demonizing
black and Hispanic people particularly.

01:09:13.691 --> 01:09:17.361
I don't think we show black
and Hispanic people as being criminals –

01:09:19.572 --> 01:09:23.783
I'd like to say not more often,
but probably they are more often.

01:09:23.868 --> 01:09:29.456
But, um, we're certainly not trying to
demonize black and Hispanic people.

01:09:29.541 --> 01:09:31.166
We show them on the news.

01:09:31.251 --> 01:09:35.002
We show them on TV as pretty scary people.

01:09:35.964 --> 01:09:37.756
Yeah.

01:09:37.841 --> 01:09:41.801
And I agree. I'd like to see that
reversed as much as possible.

01:09:41.886 --> 01:09:44.179
I, um –

01:09:44.264 --> 01:09:46.055
Start tonight.

01:09:46.140 --> 01:09:48.140
The thing is,
I don't know how to start tonight.

01:09:48.225 --> 01:09:50.352
I don't know how to tell that story.

01:09:50.435 --> 01:09:52.270
If I was smart enough to do that –

01:09:52.354 --> 01:09:55.107
-I'll pitch you one.
-Okay. All right.

01:09:55.191 --> 01:09:57.860
Um, do a show called –

01:09:57.944 --> 01:10:00.362
Not Cops, but Corporate Cops.

01:10:00.446 --> 01:10:02.030
♪ Corporation man ♪

01:10:02.115 --> 01:10:03.949
♪ Hey, corporate man ♪

01:10:04.033 --> 01:10:06.618
♪ We're coming out to get you
Better run while you can ♪

01:10:06.703 --> 01:10:09.329
♪ We're coming out to get you
Better run while you can ♪

01:10:09.414 --> 01:10:11.707
I love the idea.

01:10:11.791 --> 01:10:14.960
I don't think it would make
very interesting reality TV

01:10:15.044 --> 01:10:18.589
unless we can get those people
to get in their SUVs

01:10:18.673 --> 01:10:21.800
and drive really fast down the road
away from the police.

01:10:21.885 --> 01:10:26.221
But I'm telling you, everyone in America
who's got your basic, everyday job

01:10:26.306 --> 01:10:28.849
is gonna love watching the boss

01:10:28.933 --> 01:10:30.934
being chased down the street
with his shirt off,

01:10:31.019 --> 01:10:32.477
thrown to the ground
and a knee to the neck.

01:10:32.562 --> 01:10:34.354
I'm telling you, that is gonna get ratings.

01:10:34.439 --> 01:10:37.983
I'm with you,
and if I can find a police outfit

01:10:38.067 --> 01:10:42.404
that would prosecute corporate criminals
appropriately

01:10:42.488 --> 01:10:44.031
and would go after them appropriately –

01:10:44.115 --> 01:10:49.244
In other words, what you do to a man
who's just stolen a lady's purse with $85 to it,

01:10:49.329 --> 01:10:53.457
then you need to do
an appropriate response to a man

01:10:53.541 --> 01:10:57.002
who's just stolen $85 million
from indigent people.

01:10:57.086 --> 01:10:59.171
Then, boy,
we're gonna be out there filming that.

01:10:59.255 --> 01:11:01.465
But as a matter of fact,
when police go after the guy

01:11:01.549 --> 01:11:03.550
who's just stolen $85 million,

01:11:03.635 --> 01:11:05.636
they treat him like he was a member
of the city council,

01:11:05.720 --> 01:11:07.554
as he may or may not be,

01:11:07.639 --> 01:11:10.307
and it's not exciting television.

01:11:11.392 --> 01:11:14.478
If you could get that guy
to take his shirt off –

01:11:14.562 --> 01:11:15.771
Right.

01:11:15.855 --> 01:11:19.066
And throw his cellular phone at the police
as they come through the door,

01:11:19.150 --> 01:11:22.110
try to jump out that window,
then we'd have a show.

01:11:22.195 --> 01:11:24.863
You watch violence on TV
in a place like Canada,

01:11:24.948 --> 01:11:27.032
and you know it's not happening next door.

01:11:27.116 --> 01:11:30.953
You watch it here,
and you know it is happening next door.

01:11:31.037 --> 01:11:33.246
-Right.
-I think that's –

01:11:33.331 --> 01:11:35.958
I don't know what the difference is,
but there's a big difference.

01:11:36.042 --> 01:11:38.293
Why isn't it happening in Canada?

01:11:38.378 --> 01:11:42.631
Why aren't there 10,000 murders a year?

01:11:42.715 --> 01:11:45.008
I don't know,
but I want to go to Canada to retire

01:11:45.093 --> 01:11:48.178
'cause it sounds like where we want to be.

01:11:48.262 --> 01:11:51.014
I'd like to find out
what that difference is, wouldn't you?

01:11:51.099 --> 01:11:52.975
Yeah. I'm trying to find out.

01:12:00.566 --> 01:12:02.442
Where are you supposed to be now?

01:12:02.527 --> 01:12:03.860
-School.
-School.

01:12:03.945 --> 01:12:05.570
School.

01:12:05.655 --> 01:12:07.406
Aren't you worried
about what you're not learning?

01:12:07.490 --> 01:12:11.410
I'm mostly helping everybody else in the class.
Then I barely get to do my work, period.

01:12:11.494 --> 01:12:12.911
--How about you?

01:12:12.996 --> 01:12:16.081
-You're not worried about your education?
-Well, I've got the textbook.

01:12:16.165 --> 01:12:20.127
Why do you think we have
so many gun murders in America?

01:12:20.211 --> 01:12:22.462
I have no idea.

01:12:22.547 --> 01:12:25.048
People must hate each other there
or something.

01:12:25.133 --> 01:12:26.925
You mean Canadians don't hate each other?

01:12:27.010 --> 01:12:31.388
Well, we do, but we don't go to the point
of shooting somebody just to get revenge.

01:12:31.472 --> 01:12:35.100
-What do you do?
-I don't know. Tease them, maybe.

01:12:35.184 --> 01:12:37.269
-Make fun of them, ridicule them.
-Throw eggs at them.

01:12:37.353 --> 01:12:38.395
-Eggs.
-Eggs.

01:12:38.479 --> 01:12:41.273
How many gun murders in Sarnia this year?

01:12:41.357 --> 01:12:42.357
None.

01:12:42.442 --> 01:12:44.526
Last year?

01:12:44.610 --> 01:12:46.653
I believe we had one at the time.

01:12:46.738 --> 01:12:48.321
Year before that?

01:12:48.406 --> 01:12:50.449
I can't recall what we had in the way of –

01:12:50.533 --> 01:12:53.160
-Maybe one in the last three years?
-Probably. Yes.

01:12:53.244 --> 01:12:56.163
-Mm-hmm.
-Very low. Very low for the city.

01:12:56.247 --> 01:12:57.247
Mm-hmm.

01:12:57.331 --> 01:13:01.251
Well, of course there's no murders here
because there's only 70,000 people

01:13:01.335 --> 01:13:04.087
and it's "The Kissing Capital of the World."

01:13:04.172 --> 01:13:06.590
So I went down the river
to another Canadian city

01:13:06.674 --> 01:13:09.217
that was five times as large as Sarnia –

01:13:09.302 --> 01:13:13.138
Windsor, Ontario,
just across the river from Detroit.

01:13:13.222 --> 01:13:16.016
I was sure there'd be
more murders in Windsor.

01:13:16.100 --> 01:13:18.852
Ever hear of anyone
being shot by a gun in Windsor?

01:13:18.936 --> 01:13:21.188
No. No.

01:13:21.272 --> 01:13:23.273
You remember any murders here?

01:13:23.357 --> 01:13:26.860
There was one long time ago probably.

01:13:26.944 --> 01:13:29.154
- How long ago?
-–

01:13:30.406 --> 01:13:32.240
-In your lifetime?
-In my lifetime.

01:13:32.325 --> 01:13:35.535
Probably about 15, 20 years ago,
there was one murder.

01:13:35.620 --> 01:13:37.788
In fact, this Windsor policeman told me

01:13:37.872 --> 01:13:41.875
that the only gun murder he could recall
in Windsor in the last three years

01:13:41.959 --> 01:13:44.461
was committed by a guy from Detroit

01:13:44.545 --> 01:13:46.546
who had a stolen gun from Minnesota.

01:13:46.631 --> 01:13:50.467
With nearly 400,000 people
in the Windsor area,

01:13:50.551 --> 01:13:54.888
there were simply no Canadians
shooting other Canadians.

01:13:56.599 --> 01:13:59.643
I thought it might be time
for some fun facts about Canada.

01:14:00.603 --> 01:14:02.896
I hit the streets of New York to find out

01:14:02.980 --> 01:14:06.858
what the average American thought
about our friendly neighbor to the north.

01:14:06.943 --> 01:14:11.655
Canadians don't watch as much
violent movies as Americans do.

01:14:17.578 --> 01:14:20.705
That's wrong. Hordes of young boys
all throughout Canada

01:14:20.790 --> 01:14:23.375
eagerly await
the next Hollywood bloodbath.

01:14:23.459 --> 01:14:26.711
- Then the guy gets his leg taken off.
- Wow.

01:14:26.796 --> 01:14:29.131
-And there was a lot of girls.
-Showing cleavage.

01:14:29.215 --> 01:14:30.715
-And naked.
-Yeah?

01:14:30.800 --> 01:14:32.509
-Naked at one point.
-I like that stuff.

01:14:32.593 --> 01:14:35.679
-What movie did you guys see tonight?
-Sixth Day.

01:14:35.763 --> 01:14:37.931
-Sixth Day with Arnold Schwarzenegger?
-Yeah.

01:14:38.808 --> 01:14:42.227
Did it make you want to come out here
and play this shoot-'em-up game?

01:14:42.311 --> 01:14:45.063
Well, yeah.

01:14:45.148 --> 01:14:50.026
There's no poverty in Canada
like there is here in the States.

01:14:50.111 --> 01:14:51.278
Wrong again.

01:14:51.362 --> 01:14:54.156
We've also had much higher unemployment rate.

01:14:54.240 --> 01:14:56.074
When Michigan was running at four percent,

01:14:56.159 --> 01:14:57.993
we were still running at eight or nine percent.

01:14:58.077 --> 01:15:00.162
We had an institutional unemployment rate.

01:15:00.246 --> 01:15:02.539
I think there'd mostly be white people
in Canada.

01:15:02.623 --> 01:15:04.416
That's strange.

01:15:04.500 --> 01:15:07.586
'Cause when I'm in Canada,
I see black people everywhere.

01:15:07.670 --> 01:15:10.005
And yellow people and brown people.

01:15:10.089 --> 01:15:12.924
And 13 percent of the country is nonwhite.

01:15:13.342 --> 01:15:16.469
So the Canadians are pretty much just like us,

01:15:16.554 --> 01:15:19.097
and the reason that they have so few murders

01:15:19.182 --> 01:15:22.184
has to be because they've got so few guns.

01:15:27.356 --> 01:15:29.316
What kind of guns do you own?

01:15:29.400 --> 01:15:31.818
I hunt. I own rifles and shotguns.

01:15:31.903 --> 01:15:33.778
-I own pistols.
-Mm-hmm.

01:15:33.863 --> 01:15:35.864
So how many guns total?

01:15:35.948 --> 01:15:37.991
-Probably about seven.
-Seven guns?

01:15:38.075 --> 01:15:40.118
-Do you have a gun?
-I have a few guns.

01:15:40.203 --> 01:15:42.913
-Really? How many guns do you have?
-Half a dozen.

01:15:42.997 --> 01:15:46.249
You could name how many people right now
that own guns that you know?

01:15:46.334 --> 01:15:49.252
-Two, three, a dozen?
-More than that.

01:15:49.337 --> 01:15:52.422
There's a tremendous amount of gun ownership,
being the nature of the country we are.

01:15:52.506 --> 01:15:54.299
We're a large country geographically.

01:15:54.383 --> 01:15:56.384
We grew up with hunting and fishing
being a tradition.

01:15:56.469 --> 01:15:59.304
In Canada, with a population
of just around about 30 million,

01:15:59.388 --> 01:16:01.389
there's about ten million families,

01:16:01.474 --> 01:16:04.851
and the best estimate is
somewhere in the region of seven million guns.

01:16:05.728 --> 01:16:11.608
Wow. Canada was one gun-loving,
gun-toting, gun-crazy country.

01:16:13.194 --> 01:16:16.154
-Where can I get a gun?
-I can buy a gun uptown anytime I want to.

01:16:16.239 --> 01:16:19.991
I see you're a Glock owner.
Where can I get a Glock in Canada?

01:16:21.410 --> 01:16:24.955
Most gun stores will sell them to you
if you have the proper permits.

01:16:25.039 --> 01:16:27.791
In fact, despite all their tough gun laws,

01:16:27.875 --> 01:16:30.418
take a look at what I, a foreign citizen,

01:16:30.503 --> 01:16:33.588
was able to do
at the local Canadian Walmart.

01:16:33.673 --> 01:16:36.341
-Where's the ammunition at?
-Where's the ammunition?

01:16:36.425 --> 01:16:38.051
-Yeah.
-Back here.

01:16:41.514 --> 01:16:44.432
-What kind are you looking for?
-You know, like, bullets.

01:16:47.019 --> 01:16:48.186
That's right.

01:16:48.271 --> 01:16:52.816
I could buy as much live ammunition
as I wanted to in Canada.

01:16:52.900 --> 01:16:54.067
Do you take American?

01:16:54.151 --> 01:16:56.653
-Do you lock your doors?
-No.

01:16:56.737 --> 01:16:59.072
Are you afraid of anything?

01:16:59.156 --> 01:17:01.157
Not normally, no.

01:17:01.242 --> 01:17:03.451
-Do you lock your doors at night?
-No.

01:17:03.536 --> 01:17:05.578
-You don't lock your doors?
-No.

01:17:05.663 --> 01:17:08.039
What are you – Are you afraid of anything?

01:17:08.124 --> 01:17:09.332
Not really.

01:17:09.417 --> 01:17:11.918
-Have you ever been broken into?
-Yes, I have.

01:17:13.170 --> 01:17:14.754
What happened?

01:17:14.839 --> 01:17:16.673
They broke into my home. I wasn't there.

01:17:16.757 --> 01:17:20.635
They broke in, they stole some booze,
some cigarettes, and they left.

01:17:20.720 --> 01:17:25.348
So I figured it must've been some teenagers
out to have a little bit of fun.

01:17:25.433 --> 01:17:28.310
That's all they took though –
some booze and some cigarettes.

01:17:28.394 --> 01:17:30.520
-Have you ever been a victim of crime?
-Yes.

01:17:30.604 --> 01:17:32.355
What kind of crime?

01:17:32.440 --> 01:17:34.899
I've had people walk in
while I've been sleeping

01:17:34.984 --> 01:17:38.320
and vandalize my home and steal from me.

01:17:38.404 --> 01:17:40.739
And that didn't want to make you
lock your doors at night?

01:17:40.823 --> 01:17:43.533
Nope. No.

01:17:43.617 --> 01:17:46.411
As an American
with three locks on his doors,

01:17:46.495 --> 01:17:48.538
I found this all a bit confusing.

01:17:48.622 --> 01:17:53.543
Even here in Toronto, a city of millions,
people just didn't lock their doors.

01:17:53.627 --> 01:17:55.754
So you don't lock your doors,
but we Americans do.

01:17:55.838 --> 01:17:57.589
Why is that?

01:17:57.673 --> 01:17:59.674
You must be afraid of your neighbor.

01:17:59.759 --> 01:18:02.385
Do you ever leave your doors
unlocked at home?

01:18:02.470 --> 01:18:04.679
-Yes.
-Yeah? You do?

01:18:04.764 --> 01:18:06.598
-Where do you live?
-Right around here.

01:18:06.682 --> 01:18:07.974
-Toronto?
-Around here.

01:18:08.059 --> 01:18:09.726
-And you leave your doors unlocked?
-Yeah.

01:18:09.810 --> 01:18:11.644
You think, as Americans,

01:18:11.729 --> 01:18:15.648
that the lock is keeping people
out of your place.

01:18:15.733 --> 01:18:19.194
We, as Canadians, see it more as

01:18:19.278 --> 01:18:22.864
when we lock the door,
we're imprisoning ourselves inside.

01:18:22.948 --> 01:18:25.784
-You don't want to do that.
-Not really, no.

01:18:25.868 --> 01:18:27.702
We don't want to –

01:18:28.871 --> 01:18:30.246
No.

01:18:30.331 --> 01:18:33.792
I decided to go unannounced
to a neighborhood in Toronto

01:18:33.876 --> 01:18:36.628
to see if this unlocked door thing was true.

01:18:37.546 --> 01:18:39.756
Hi. Sorry. Just checking.

01:18:45.054 --> 01:18:46.596
--Hello.

01:18:53.229 --> 01:18:54.854
- Hi.
- Hi.

01:18:54.939 --> 01:18:58.942
Nobody locks their doors.
Nobody locks their doors in this town!

01:18:59.026 --> 01:19:01.861
-You want it locked?
-No, no, no.

01:19:01.946 --> 01:19:03.905
-You like living here?
-I like it very much.

01:19:03.989 --> 01:19:06.366
-And the T-shirt?
-The T-shirt too.

01:19:06.450 --> 01:19:09.494
This door was wide open.
And you're not afraid?

01:19:09.578 --> 01:19:11.413
-Should I be afraid?
-I don't know. You live here.

01:19:11.497 --> 01:19:13.206
-I don't think I'm afraid.
-You're not, are you?

01:19:13.290 --> 01:19:14.707
-Thank you very much.
-All right. No problem.

01:19:14.792 --> 01:19:17.168
-I'm sorry about the intrusion.
-No problem.

01:19:17.253 --> 01:19:20.004
-And thank you for not shooting me.
-No problem. No, no, no.

01:19:20.089 --> 01:19:21.214
-Bye-bye.
-Okay.

01:19:21.298 --> 01:19:25.093
As an American, I gotta say
this all seemed kind of strange

01:19:25.177 --> 01:19:27.929
until I looked up at the TV in the bar

01:19:28.013 --> 01:19:31.182
and noticed what they watch
for their evening news.

01:19:31.267 --> 01:19:32.600
They're friends of ours.

01:19:32.685 --> 01:19:36.146
We'll certainly listen to them
courteously and carefully.

01:19:36.230 --> 01:19:39.691
But you don't just make war
just 'cause someone says so.

01:19:39.775 --> 01:19:43.736
Night after night, the Canadians
weren't being pumped full of fear.

01:19:43.821 --> 01:19:46.781
And their politicians
seemed to talk kind of funny.

01:19:46.866 --> 01:19:48.867
Making sure they have proper day care,

01:19:48.951 --> 01:19:51.202
that they have assistance
for their parents when they're elderly

01:19:51.287 --> 01:19:52.912
and need to be in an old age home,

01:19:52.997 --> 01:19:56.916
that they have proper health care that ensures
they won't lose their business or their house

01:19:57.001 --> 01:19:58.793
because they can't afford
their medical bills.

01:19:58.878 --> 01:20:00.378
That's how you build a good society.

01:20:00.463 --> 01:20:01.963
No one wins unless everyone wins,

01:20:02.047 --> 01:20:04.757
and you don't win by beating up on people
who can't defend themselves.

01:20:04.842 --> 01:20:09.053
That's been the approach spreading in some
right-wing governments across North America.

01:20:09.138 --> 01:20:11.764
They pick on the people
that can't defend themselves,

01:20:11.849 --> 01:20:14.851
and at the same time, they're turning around
and giving financial support

01:20:14.935 --> 01:20:18.062
and tax breaks and tax benefits
to people that don't need them.

01:20:18.147 --> 01:20:20.940
Where are the indigent in this city?
Where do they live?

01:20:22.067 --> 01:20:23.776
Indigent?

01:20:23.861 --> 01:20:26.654
You act like you've never heard
the word before.

01:20:26.739 --> 01:20:30.116
There's – We don't have
that problem here, really.

01:20:30.201 --> 01:20:33.161
So I asked him, "Could you at least
take me to a Canadian slum?"

01:20:33.245 --> 01:20:37.832
And, well, this is what
a ghetto looks like in Canada.

01:20:37.917 --> 01:20:41.127
Is this the same sort of mentality
that says, with Canadians,

01:20:41.212 --> 01:20:43.505
you think if somebody gets sick,

01:20:43.589 --> 01:20:45.465
they should actually be able
to have health care?

01:20:45.549 --> 01:20:47.383
- Definitely.
- Yes.

01:20:47.468 --> 01:20:49.302
Yeah.

01:20:49.386 --> 01:20:51.179
Why?

01:20:51.263 --> 01:20:52.764
-Because!
-Human rights.

01:20:52.848 --> 01:20:54.390
Everyone's got the right to live.

01:20:54.475 --> 01:20:56.809
-Did you just come out of the emergency room?
-Yes, I did.

01:20:56.894 --> 01:20:59.187
And how much did you have to pay
for your treatment?

01:20:59.271 --> 01:21:03.483
I wouldn't know what the bill is.
It's covered by our hospital plan.

01:21:03.567 --> 01:21:06.110
-You're telling me you didn't have to pay anything?
-No, I don't.

01:21:06.195 --> 01:21:08.279
I have family that lives in the States.

01:21:08.364 --> 01:21:11.032
They used to live in Canada
and moved over there,

01:21:11.116 --> 01:21:12.951
and it's so different.

01:21:13.035 --> 01:21:16.371
- They get afraid more easily.
- Yeah.

01:21:16.455 --> 01:21:18.831
Yup. Very much so.

01:21:18.916 --> 01:21:23.002
Because everybody reacts
over there just like that.

01:21:23.087 --> 01:21:25.505
They don't stop and think.

01:21:25.589 --> 01:21:27.674
First reaction is pull the gun up.

01:21:27.758 --> 01:21:30.176
"You're on my property."

01:21:30.261 --> 01:21:31.761
You know, like –

01:21:33.180 --> 01:21:36.724
I don't know. It's just different over here.

01:21:36.809 --> 01:21:38.935
-Where do you live?
-Detroit.

01:21:39.019 --> 01:21:41.938
-Come over to Canada for the night?
-Right.

01:21:42.022 --> 01:21:45.191
People are a little more open-minded here,
a little more welcoming.

01:21:45.276 --> 01:21:48.111
Feel any difference
when you cross over to this country?

01:21:48.195 --> 01:21:50.113
-Be honest now. Come on.
-It's a lot lighter.

01:21:50.197 --> 01:21:54.742
The segregation over there is definitely
much more intensified in the States.

01:21:54.827 --> 01:21:56.661
Yeah.

01:21:56.745 --> 01:21:58.329
So you can feel it.

01:21:58.414 --> 01:22:00.832
Almost like they just let you be.

01:22:00.916 --> 01:22:02.333
That's Canada for you.

01:22:02.418 --> 01:22:06.379
Every time I turn on the TV in the States,
it's always about a murder here,

01:22:06.463 --> 01:22:08.631
a gunfight, hostile position.

01:22:08.716 --> 01:22:12.343
I just think the States,
their view of things is fighting.

01:22:12.428 --> 01:22:14.137
That's how they resolve everything.

01:22:14.221 --> 01:22:16.723
If there's something going on
in another country,

01:22:16.807 --> 01:22:20.268
they send people over to fight it.

01:22:20.352 --> 01:22:22.812
They are the most powerful country
in the world though. Sorry.

01:22:22.896 --> 01:22:25.106
Canada's more like, "Let's negotiate.
Let's work something out,"

01:22:25.190 --> 01:22:28.443
where the States is, "We'll just kill you,
and that'll be the end of that."

01:22:28.527 --> 01:22:31.446
Um, if guns were –

01:22:31.530 --> 01:22:33.906
If more guns made people safer,

01:22:33.991 --> 01:22:36.909
then America would be one
of the safest countries in the world.

01:22:36.994 --> 01:22:38.661
It isn't. It's the opposite.

01:23:22.623 --> 01:23:25.458
I heard that 911 call on TV someplace.

01:23:25.542 --> 01:23:27.835
It was horrible. It was just –

01:23:27.920 --> 01:23:31.297
He kept saying, "Where's the shooter?"
She said, "He's gone. I need some help."

01:23:31.382 --> 01:23:34.008
- And the little girl was in there too?
- She was on the floor.

01:23:34.093 --> 01:23:35.885
-She was on the floor?
-Mm-hmm.

01:23:35.969 --> 01:23:37.929
And the police and the medics came?

01:23:38.013 --> 01:23:41.391
By that time, the medics were here.
The medics had just come in.

01:23:41.475 --> 01:23:44.227
And I remember him stepping in
and taking over the room.

01:23:44.311 --> 01:23:46.521
-He says, "You have to leave."
-Right.

01:23:46.605 --> 01:23:49.565
And then when the medics come in,
when the police come in,

01:23:49.650 --> 01:23:51.442
you're no longer in control.

01:23:51.527 --> 01:23:53.945
Was she still alive then? Probably not.

01:23:54.029 --> 01:23:56.406
Her lips had begun to turn blue.

01:23:57.700 --> 01:24:00.076
Back in my hometown of Flint, Michigan,

01:24:00.160 --> 01:24:03.913
a six-year-old, first-grade boy
at Buell Elementary

01:24:03.997 --> 01:24:07.417
had found a gun at his uncle's house
where he was staying

01:24:07.501 --> 01:24:09.919
because his mother was being evicted.

01:24:10.003 --> 01:24:13.923
He brought the gun to school
and shot another first-grader,

01:24:14.007 --> 01:24:17.093
six-year-old Kayla Rolland.

01:24:17.177 --> 01:24:19.470
With one bullet
that passed through her body,

01:24:19.555 --> 01:24:22.223
she fell to the floor and laid there dying

01:24:22.307 --> 01:24:25.852
while her teacher called 911 for help.

01:24:25.936 --> 01:24:29.522
No one knew why the little boy
wanted to shoot the little girl.

01:24:29.606 --> 01:24:34.527
As if the city had not been through enough
horror and tragedy in the past two decades,

01:24:34.611 --> 01:24:37.113
it was now home to a new record –

01:24:37.197 --> 01:24:40.783
the youngest school shooting ever
in the United States.

01:24:41.577 --> 01:24:43.578
On the morning of the shooting,

01:24:43.662 --> 01:24:47.707
it only took the news helicopters
and satellite trucks a half hour

01:24:47.791 --> 01:24:49.250
to show up on the scene.

01:24:49.334 --> 01:24:50.960
Leave your mike on.

01:24:51.044 --> 01:24:54.046
They're checking the truck.
We're doing one in 30 minutes.

01:24:54.131 --> 01:24:57.008
This evening about 7:00
will be a public memorial service.

01:24:57.092 --> 01:24:59.886
We are expecting hundreds of people.

01:24:59.970 --> 01:25:01.554
They will mourn the loss of little Kayla,

01:25:01.638 --> 01:25:04.557
a tiny little girl
who loved pizza, teddy bears

01:25:04.641 --> 01:25:06.851
and who was taken away from us
much too soon.

01:25:06.935 --> 01:25:07.769
Gina?

01:25:07.853 --> 01:25:09.270
Good morning, Christine.

01:25:09.354 --> 01:25:12.398
The funeral home now passing out
tens of thousands of these pink ribbons

01:25:12.483 --> 01:25:14.484
to support the young girl's family.

01:25:14.568 --> 01:25:18.988
Today will be an emotional day
and has been already, remembering little Kayla.

01:25:19.072 --> 01:25:20.698
Jeff Rossen, Fox 2 News.

01:25:23.285 --> 01:25:24.786
Nice job.

01:25:26.705 --> 01:25:29.457
Yeah, Michelle,
we're having technical problems, okay?

01:25:29.541 --> 01:25:32.585
Well, don't talk to me about it.
Call our sat truck.

01:25:33.962 --> 01:25:36.088
I need a haircut, man. I'm a pig.

01:25:36.173 --> 01:25:37.548
A rug.

01:25:37.633 --> 01:25:39.133
Here we go.

01:25:44.932 --> 01:25:47.099
Some too choked up even to speak about it.

01:25:47.184 --> 01:25:50.061
There's a memorial service
scheduled here for 7:00 tonight.

01:25:50.145 --> 01:25:52.313
We're live in Flint, Michigan this afternoon.

01:25:52.397 --> 01:25:54.398
Jeff Rossen, Q13 reports.

01:25:58.946 --> 01:26:00.822
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

01:26:02.658 --> 01:26:04.951
- I kind of need it, don't I?
- Yeah, you do.

01:26:05.828 --> 01:26:08.454
I have some. I just didn't put it in.
I didn't have a chance.

01:26:09.748 --> 01:26:13.292
This man prayed for Kayla,
then let the balloon go.

01:26:14.253 --> 01:26:17.046
I see we have the color picture,
not the black and white card.

01:26:17.130 --> 01:26:19.340
There are plenty of media here
that covered Columbine.

01:26:19.424 --> 01:26:21.717
There are some networks, especially,

01:26:21.802 --> 01:26:24.887
that go from, unfortunately,
tragedy to tragedy.

01:26:24.972 --> 01:26:28.558
And I feel bad for them
because that's all they see.

01:26:30.102 --> 01:26:32.019
Tragedies.

01:26:33.856 --> 01:26:37.066
We're just trying to crunch right now
for the 5:00 and the 6:00.

01:26:38.485 --> 01:26:41.612
Today we're feeding CNN and Fox, so...

01:26:42.447 --> 01:26:45.741
The national media
had never visited Buell Elementary

01:26:45.826 --> 01:26:48.828
or the Beecher school district
in which it sat,

01:26:48.912 --> 01:26:51.330
or this part of Flint ever before.

01:26:52.124 --> 01:26:54.876
And few, if any,
of these reporters bothered to visit it

01:26:54.960 --> 01:26:57.545
even when they were here now.

01:26:57.629 --> 01:27:01.841
If they had ventured just a block away
from the school or the funeral home,

01:27:01.925 --> 01:27:03.968
they might have seen
a different kind of tragedy

01:27:04.052 --> 01:27:08.556
that perhaps would contain some answers
as to why this little girl was dead.

01:27:11.351 --> 01:27:13.644
For over 20 years, this impoverished area

01:27:13.729 --> 01:27:16.856
in the hometown
of the world's largest corporation,

01:27:16.940 --> 01:27:19.817
had been ignored as completely
as it had been destroyed.

01:27:20.944 --> 01:27:25.281
With 87 percent of the students
living below the official poverty line,

01:27:25.365 --> 01:27:27.950
Buell and Beecher and Flint

01:27:28.035 --> 01:27:31.412
did not fit into the accepted
and widely circulated story line

01:27:31.496 --> 01:27:34.165
put forth by the nation's media.

01:27:36.293 --> 01:27:40.588
That being the one about America
and its invincible economy.

01:27:45.928 --> 01:27:49.305
The number-one cause of death
among young people in this part of Flint

01:27:49.389 --> 01:27:51.098
was homicide.

01:27:51.183 --> 01:27:55.019
The football field at Flint Beecher
was sponsored by a funeral home.

01:27:57.940 --> 01:28:02.360
The kids at Beecher have won
13 state track championships,

01:28:02.444 --> 01:28:04.820
but they've never had a home track meet

01:28:04.905 --> 01:28:09.408
because around the football field
all they have is this dirt ring.

01:28:13.038 --> 01:28:17.333
Years ago, someone here named
the streets in this part of town

01:28:17.417 --> 01:28:19.543
after all the Ivy League schools,

01:28:20.420 --> 01:28:24.924
as if they dreamed of better days
and something greater for themselves.

01:28:33.475 --> 01:28:35.726
The children are doing well.

01:28:35.811 --> 01:28:39.647
Faculty and staff are doing well.
But we don't forget.

01:28:39.731 --> 01:28:41.232
We don't forget.

01:28:42.901 --> 01:28:46.445
I just don't want this to happen
to anybody else.

01:28:46.530 --> 01:28:48.823
--I know.

01:28:49.992 --> 01:28:52.994
I know. I don't want it to happen
to anybody else either.

01:28:54.079 --> 01:28:56.455
- I thought it would, um –
- It's okay.

01:28:56.540 --> 01:28:58.457
It's okay.

01:28:58.542 --> 01:29:00.543
It's okay.

01:29:00.627 --> 01:29:02.128
It's okay.

01:29:05.173 --> 01:29:07.758
--I'm sorry.

01:29:07.843 --> 01:29:09.468
That's all right.

01:29:11.972 --> 01:29:14.390
From my cold, dead hands!

01:29:17.477 --> 01:29:20.312
Just as he did
after the Columbine shooting,

01:29:20.397 --> 01:29:24.650
Charlton Heston showed up in Flint
to have a big, pro-gun rally.

01:29:25.444 --> 01:29:28.529
Freedom has never seen greater peril

01:29:28.613 --> 01:29:33.159
nor needed you more urgently
to come to her defense than now.

01:29:33.243 --> 01:29:35.828
Before he came to Flint,
Heston was interviewed

01:29:35.912 --> 01:29:38.330
by The Georgetown Hoya
about Kayla's death,

01:29:38.415 --> 01:29:41.125
and even his own NRA website
talked about it.

01:29:41.209 --> 01:29:45.463
We wanted to let the NRA know that
we haven't forgotten about Kayla Rolland.

01:29:45.547 --> 01:29:49.008
How could they come here?
To me, it's like they're rubbing our nose in it.

01:29:49.092 --> 01:29:52.053
I was shocked and appalled
that they were coming.

01:29:52.137 --> 01:29:55.473
Heston was asked
by a local reporter why he came to Flint

01:29:55.557 --> 01:29:58.142
after the tragedy of Buell

01:29:58.226 --> 01:30:03.147
and what did the NRA have to say
about six-year-olds using guns?

01:30:03.231 --> 01:30:07.151
We spend $21 million every year.

01:30:07.235 --> 01:30:10.404
We teach it to five and six-year-olds.

01:30:10.489 --> 01:30:13.824
We say if you see a gun, don't touch it.

01:30:13.909 --> 01:30:15.910
Leave the room. Call an adult.

01:30:16.870 --> 01:30:19.830
And then Moses himself showed up.

01:30:19.915 --> 01:30:22.583
- Right here in the city of Flint?
- Right here in Flint.

01:30:22.667 --> 01:30:25.419
Were there people
that wanted you to try this child?

01:30:25.504 --> 01:30:27.171
Or even try him as an adult?

01:30:27.255 --> 01:30:29.799
Yeah.

01:30:29.883 --> 01:30:32.802
There were people from all over America

01:30:32.886 --> 01:30:35.554
that wrote and called and sent mail.

01:30:35.639 --> 01:30:38.432
It was amazing to me.

01:30:38.517 --> 01:30:41.894
Groups that were affiliated with the NRA,

01:30:41.978 --> 01:30:45.940
groups that –
people that I call gun nuts –

01:30:46.024 --> 01:30:48.567
writing me and telling me
what a horrible thing it was

01:30:48.652 --> 01:30:53.072
that I had admonished homeowners
in our country

01:30:53.156 --> 01:30:56.659
to be careful about bringing weapons
into their home.

01:30:56.743 --> 01:31:00.246
They wanted this little boy hung
from the highest tree.

01:31:00.330 --> 01:31:05.626
There was such an undercurrent
of racism and hate and anger.

01:31:05.710 --> 01:31:08.796
Um... it was ugly.

01:31:08.880 --> 01:31:13.050
That's a picture that the little boy
that was involved in the Buell School shooting,

01:31:13.135 --> 01:31:15.469
once he was brought back here
to our office

01:31:15.554 --> 01:31:18.139
about 15 minutes
after the shooting took place.

01:31:18.223 --> 01:31:21.475
I gave him some crayons and stuff
to occupy him a little bit.

01:31:21.560 --> 01:31:24.103
He came over and drew that picture for me

01:31:24.187 --> 01:31:27.565
because at the time, I had pictures
behind my desk that my children drew for me,

01:31:27.649 --> 01:31:29.775
and he wanted to draw me one
to hang behind my desk.

01:31:29.860 --> 01:31:32.695
This is what he drew for you.
What did he say this was?

01:31:32.779 --> 01:31:34.405
That's him at his house.

01:31:34.489 --> 01:31:36.574
That's him at his house, right here.

01:31:37.450 --> 01:31:39.785
And why did you decide to hang onto it?

01:31:41.163 --> 01:31:44.081
Because of the gravity of the situation
and what had occurred.

01:31:44.166 --> 01:31:46.167
And he asked me
to hang that behind my desk,

01:31:46.251 --> 01:31:49.545
so I put it in a frame,
and that's where it will stay.

01:31:52.090 --> 01:31:55.384
Tamarla Owens was the mother
of the six-year-old boy.

01:31:55.468 --> 01:31:58.721
In order to get food stamps
and health care for her children,

01:31:58.805 --> 01:32:01.891
Tamarla was forced to work
as part of the state of Michigan's

01:32:01.975 --> 01:32:04.435
Welfare to Work program.

01:32:05.103 --> 01:32:09.190
This program was so successful
in tossing poor people off welfare,

01:32:09.274 --> 01:32:11.317
that its founder, Gerald Miller,

01:32:11.401 --> 01:32:14.069
was soon hired
by the number-one firm in the country

01:32:14.154 --> 01:32:17.531
that states turn to
to privatize their welfare systems.

01:32:18.575 --> 01:32:21.076
That firm was Lockheed Martin.

01:32:22.120 --> 01:32:26.165
With the Cold War over
and no enemy left to frighten the public,

01:32:26.249 --> 01:32:29.001
Lockheed had found
the perfect way to diversify

01:32:29.085 --> 01:32:32.004
and the perfect way
to profit from people's fears

01:32:32.088 --> 01:32:34.715
with an enemy much closer to home –

01:32:34.799 --> 01:32:38.344
poor black mothers like Tamarla Owens.

01:32:38.428 --> 01:32:40.262
So you've got a one-parent family,

01:32:40.347 --> 01:32:44.141
and the mother's traveling 60 miles,
an hour and a half away to go to work,

01:32:44.226 --> 01:32:46.310
an hour and a half to come home.

01:32:46.394 --> 01:32:48.604
How does that help a community?

01:32:48.688 --> 01:32:52.274
But that's part of the state
making parents responsible,

01:32:52.359 --> 01:32:53.901
making them work for their money.

01:32:53.985 --> 01:32:55.402
-Welfare to Work.
-Welfare to Work.

01:32:55.487 --> 01:33:00.282
That's a program that ought to be stopped
because it really has no merit.

01:33:01.910 --> 01:33:04.370
I think it adds more to the problem
than it does to solve it.

01:33:04.454 --> 01:33:07.081
Really?
You're the sheriff, and you feel this way?

01:33:07.165 --> 01:33:08.874
I do. I do.

01:33:08.959 --> 01:33:12.962
I wish I could put two parents in every home
and make every parent equally responsible,

01:33:13.046 --> 01:33:14.797
but you can't do that.

01:33:14.881 --> 01:33:17.800
But we're not doing anything by taking
the one parent and putting them on a bus

01:33:17.884 --> 01:33:21.220
and sending them out of town
to make $5.50 an hour.

01:33:23.139 --> 01:33:25.933
This is the bus
that she was forced to ride every day

01:33:26.017 --> 01:33:28.727
in order to work off the welfare money
the state had given her.

01:33:32.274 --> 01:33:34.692
She and many others from Flint
who were poor

01:33:34.776 --> 01:33:37.528
would make the 80-mile round-trip journey
every day

01:33:37.612 --> 01:33:40.864
from Flint to Auburn Hills in Oakland County,

01:33:40.949 --> 01:33:43.575
one of the wealthiest areas in the country.

01:33:45.662 --> 01:33:49.456
Tamarla would leave early in the morning
and return late at night,

01:33:49.541 --> 01:33:52.501
rarely seeing her young children.

01:33:52.585 --> 01:33:55.921
What's the point in doing that?

01:33:56.006 --> 01:33:59.508
Where does the state benefit?
Where does Flint and Genesee County benefit?

01:33:59.592 --> 01:34:04.138
We have a child dead.
I think that may be part of the problem.

01:34:04.222 --> 01:34:06.223
We drove the one parent out.

01:34:08.518 --> 01:34:12.146
Now, you or anybody else that can tell me

01:34:12.230 --> 01:34:15.274
that that best serves a community,

01:34:15.358 --> 01:34:17.735
I shake my head and wonder why.

01:34:19.154 --> 01:34:21.071
How long have you been riding the bus?

01:34:21.156 --> 01:34:23.699
I've been working here
just about three years now.

01:34:23.783 --> 01:34:25.492
-About three years?
-Yeah.

01:34:25.577 --> 01:34:27.911
I got my brother working here.

01:34:27.996 --> 01:34:30.414
Half of my neighborhood works out here.

01:34:30.498 --> 01:34:33.500
Just about everybody I know personally
works out here in the mall.

01:34:33.585 --> 01:34:37.629
In Flint, doing the same thing I'm doing now,
they only pay minimum wage.

01:34:37.714 --> 01:34:41.967
I come 40 miles to make
three or four dollars more an hour.

01:34:42.052 --> 01:34:44.595
-How much you make an hour here?
-I make 8.50 an hour.

01:34:44.679 --> 01:34:46.472
8.50?

01:34:46.556 --> 01:34:48.474
-Is that enough to pay the bills?
-No.

01:34:48.558 --> 01:34:53.729
Did you know Tamarla Owens,
the woman whose son shot the little girl?

01:34:53.813 --> 01:34:55.522
I think she rode this bus.

01:34:55.607 --> 01:34:58.317
I knew her a little bit. Not real good.

01:34:58.401 --> 01:35:00.319
-Nice lady?
-Yeah, she was okay.

01:35:00.403 --> 01:35:04.281
She came to work every day.
She did her job. She worked two jobs.

01:35:04.366 --> 01:35:07.659
-Worked two jobs?
-She was trying to make ends meet.

