I decided to fly out to California

01:36:44.174 --> 01:36:46.592
to ask Dick Clark
what he thought about a system

01:36:46.676 --> 01:36:51.889
that forces poor, single mothers
to work two low-wage jobs to survive.

01:36:51.973 --> 01:36:54.224
I'm doing a documentary

01:36:54.309 --> 01:36:57.811
on these school shootings
and guns and all that.

01:36:57.896 --> 01:37:02.441
And, um, in my hometown of Flint, Michigan,
which you know,

01:37:02.525 --> 01:37:04.985
this little six-year-old
shot a six-year-old.

01:37:05.069 --> 01:37:07.571
Get in the car, Dave.
Watch your arm. Watch your arm.

01:37:07.655 --> 01:37:10.240
- Sorry.
- I'm sorry. We're really late.

01:37:10.325 --> 01:37:14.036
Anyways, but the mother
of the kid who did the shooting

01:37:14.120 --> 01:37:16.455
works at Dick Clark's All American Grill.

01:37:16.539 --> 01:37:18.165
Forget it. Close the door.

01:37:18.249 --> 01:37:20.542
-It's a Welfare to Work program.
-Close the door.

01:37:20.627 --> 01:37:22.586
-These people are forced to – Dick.
-Bye.

01:37:22.670 --> 01:37:26.548
No, no, no. I want you to help me
to convince the governor of Michigan –

01:37:26.633 --> 01:37:30.177
It's a Welfare to Work pr –
These women are forced to work.

01:37:30.261 --> 01:37:33.680
They've got kids at home. Dick! Aw, geez!

01:37:35.058 --> 01:37:39.269
In George Bush's America,
the poor were not a priority.

01:37:39.354 --> 01:37:42.105
And after September 11, 2001,

01:37:42.190 --> 01:37:44.691
correcting America's social problems

01:37:44.776 --> 01:37:50.113
took a back seat to fear, panic,
and a new set of priorities.

01:37:50.198 --> 01:37:52.574
One way to express our unity

01:37:52.659 --> 01:37:56.662
is for Congress to set the military budget,

01:37:56.746 --> 01:37:58.622
the defense of the United States,

01:37:58.706 --> 01:38:00.624
as a number-one priority

01:38:00.708 --> 01:38:02.376
and fully fund my request.

01:38:08.007 --> 01:38:11.552
We've been selling a lot of chemical suits
with the gloves and the hoods.

01:38:11.636 --> 01:38:14.221
And we've been selling a lot of gas masks.

01:38:14.305 --> 01:38:16.557
I'm trying to get one for myself and my puppy.

01:38:16.641 --> 01:38:19.768
Dennis Marks and his wife
have been stocking up supplies.

01:38:20.728 --> 01:38:21.979
Weapons. Ammunition.

01:38:22.063 --> 01:38:26.233
Walmart says after
September 11, gun sales surged 70 percent,

01:38:26.317 --> 01:38:28.610
ammunition up 140 percent.

01:38:28.695 --> 01:38:32.739
In Dallas, they're already taking pot shots
at Osama bin Laden.

01:38:32.824 --> 01:38:35.492
In the months following the 9/11 attacks,

01:38:35.577 --> 01:38:38.579
we Americans
were gripped in a state of fear.

01:38:38.663 --> 01:38:42.249
None of us knew if we too would die
at the hands of the evildoers

01:38:42.333 --> 01:38:45.919
or who might be sitting next to some crazy guy
trying to light his shoes on fire.

01:38:46.963 --> 01:38:49.464
The threats seemed very real.

01:38:49.549 --> 01:38:53.176
It's probably a little paranoia,
but I'm not gonna take the chance, that's all.

01:38:53.261 --> 01:38:55.012
Just trying to protect myself and my family.

01:38:55.096 --> 01:38:59.141
Our growing fears were turned
into a handsome profit for many.

01:38:59.225 --> 01:39:04.104
Mike Blake has seen a 30 percent
increase in sales at ADT over the last month.

01:39:04.188 --> 01:39:09.276
Most of the people he talks to are still uneasy
over the September 11 terrorist attacks.

01:39:09.360 --> 01:39:11.111
How are we afraid of all these things?

01:39:11.195 --> 01:39:13.822
It's because a lot of people
are making a lot of money off of it

01:39:13.906 --> 01:39:16.950
and a lot of careers off of it.

01:39:17.035 --> 01:39:21.622
And so there's vested interests,
a lot of activity to keep us afraid.

01:39:21.706 --> 01:39:24.583
And what better way
to fight box cutter-wielding terrorists

01:39:24.667 --> 01:39:27.794
than to order a record number
of fighter jets from Lockheed?

01:39:27.879 --> 01:39:30.088
Yes, everyone felt safer,

01:39:30.173 --> 01:39:33.967
especially with the army doing
garbage detail on Park Avenue.

01:39:34.052 --> 01:39:37.429
And the greatest benefit of all
of a terrorized public

01:39:37.513 --> 01:39:42.267
is that the corporate and political leaders
can get away with just about anything.

01:39:42.352 --> 01:39:47.064
I've never seen a better example
of cash-and-carry government

01:39:47.148 --> 01:39:51.985
than this Bush administration and Enron.

01:39:52.070 --> 01:39:55.739
There were a lot of things I didn't know
after the World Trade Center attack,

01:39:55.823 --> 01:39:58.241
but one thing was clear.

01:39:58.326 --> 01:40:01.411
Whether it was before
or after September 11,

01:40:01.496 --> 01:40:04.247
a public that's this out of control with fear

01:40:04.332 --> 01:40:07.209
should not have a lot of guns
or ammo laying around.

01:40:10.213 --> 01:40:13.882
Well, I was shot with a Tec-9.

01:40:13.966 --> 01:40:15.926
- Nine millimeter?
- Yeah.

01:40:16.010 --> 01:40:17.511
Yeah, it was –

01:40:19.889 --> 01:40:21.848
I guess it was supposed
to be semiautomatic,

01:40:21.933 --> 01:40:24.142
but it kind of seemed
like fully automatic to me,

01:40:24.227 --> 01:40:25.644
from what I remember.

01:40:25.728 --> 01:40:27.270
This is Richard Castaldo.

01:40:28.314 --> 01:40:30.440
And this is Mark Taylor.

01:40:30.525 --> 01:40:33.777
Both of these boys were shot
the day of the Columbine massacre.

01:40:34.570 --> 01:40:37.989
Richard is paralyzed for life
and in a wheelchair.

01:40:38.074 --> 01:40:42.160
And Mark is barely standing
after numerous operations.

01:40:42.245 --> 01:40:44.746
The kids at Columbine
had to pay a penalty.

01:40:44.831 --> 01:40:48.625
We paid a penalty that day for this nation,
the way we look at it.

01:40:49.252 --> 01:40:51.628
Mark and Richard
were disabled and suffering

01:40:51.713 --> 01:40:56.133
from the 17-cent Kmart bullets
still embedded in their bodies.

01:40:56.801 --> 01:40:59.886
As they showed me
the various entry points for the bullets,

01:40:59.971 --> 01:41:04.891
I thought of one way we could reduce
the number of guns and bullets laying around.

01:41:04.976 --> 01:41:07.811
I asked the boys
if they'd like to go to Kmart

01:41:07.895 --> 01:41:10.147
to return the merchandise.

01:41:12.191 --> 01:41:14.860
- Ready?
- Y... You go.

01:41:14.944 --> 01:41:16.278
- Me?
- Yep.

01:41:32.086 --> 01:41:33.587
Cool.

01:41:34.505 --> 01:41:36.006
Okay.

01:41:45.975 --> 01:41:48.226
Do you want me to grab –

01:41:48.311 --> 01:41:50.228
- That comes out.
- Okay.

01:41:50.313 --> 01:41:51.855
There we go.

01:41:52.690 --> 01:41:54.316
Hi.

01:41:54.400 --> 01:41:57.360
-Excuse me. Turn the camera off, please.
-We're here to see Mr. Conaway.

01:41:57.445 --> 01:41:59.905
Okay, you have to turn the camera off
while you're in the building

01:41:59.989 --> 01:42:01.698
till I get clearance for you
to turn it back on.

01:42:01.783 --> 01:42:03.784
All right. Turn it off.

01:42:04.702 --> 01:42:06.495
-Hi, Michael.
-Hi. How are you?

01:42:06.579 --> 01:42:09.831
I'm Mary Lorenz.
I'm director of media relations for Kmart.

01:42:09.916 --> 01:42:11.917
- Good.
- How can I help you today?

01:42:12.001 --> 01:42:14.836
I'm here today – This is Richard Castaldo.

01:42:14.921 --> 01:42:17.631
-Richard, nice to meet you.
-And this is Mark Taylor.

01:42:17.715 --> 01:42:18.882
Mark.

01:42:18.966 --> 01:42:21.551
And they're students
from Columbine High School.

01:42:21.636 --> 01:42:25.472
They were shot at Columbine
in the massacre

01:42:25.556 --> 01:42:27.057
with bullets from Kmart.

01:42:27.141 --> 01:42:29.893
You came a long way,
all the way from Colorado.

01:42:29.977 --> 01:42:34.022
Yeah, I was just thinking that,

01:42:34.106 --> 01:42:36.149
since you stopped
selling the handguns and all,

01:42:36.234 --> 01:42:39.945
that it kind of made sense
to stop selling the bullets too.

01:42:40.029 --> 01:42:43.114
Our request is that you get rid
of the nine-millimeter bullets

01:42:43.199 --> 01:42:45.283
and that you don't sell them
in the store completely.

01:42:45.368 --> 01:42:48.119
We do carry –
You probably are aware of Kmart.

01:42:48.204 --> 01:42:50.205
Hopefully, you're shoppers of our stores.

01:42:50.289 --> 01:42:54.376
That we do only carry sporting firearms

01:42:54.460 --> 01:42:59.798
and the accessories
that go with the hunting sport.

01:42:59.882 --> 01:43:04.135
We'll certainly take your message
to our chairman and CEO, Chuck Conaway.

01:43:04.220 --> 01:43:06.596
-He's not here today.
-He's not here today?

01:43:06.681 --> 01:43:08.682
He's not here actually this whole week.

01:43:08.766 --> 01:43:10.767
Not at all during the week?

01:43:10.852 --> 01:43:14.729
Do you have a limit on the number of bullets,
ammunition that people can purchase?

01:43:14.814 --> 01:43:16.773
I can't answer these questions for you.

01:43:16.858 --> 01:43:19.442
I'm not the merchandiser
who places those products.

01:43:19.527 --> 01:43:21.027
Can we speak to that person?

01:43:21.112 --> 01:43:25.031
But I can get answers to those questions for you
if you would like to leave your card.

01:43:25.116 --> 01:43:27.284
-I can get those answers for you.
-We don't want to leave a card.

01:43:27.368 --> 01:43:30.662
Let me just be blunt. The reason why
we can't take a card and come back

01:43:30.746 --> 01:43:34.499
is because Mark here, he's got
a Kmart bullet just an inch away –

01:43:34.584 --> 01:43:36.751
-Right? From your aorta?
-Yeah.

01:43:36.836 --> 01:43:40.005
-In between my aorta and spine.
-Between your aorta and spine.

01:43:40.089 --> 01:43:42.841
I'm glad to see
that you're still able to stand.

01:43:42.925 --> 01:43:45.677
I told them
that somebody here would listen,

01:43:45.761 --> 01:43:50.724
somebody here would – would –
would take their request seriously.

01:43:50.808 --> 01:43:53.894
Not just a PR person,
but somebody who has some authority,

01:43:53.978 --> 01:43:57.480
who can answer some of the questions
that they want answered.

01:43:57.565 --> 01:44:00.901
Kmart does care about this,
but I can't go any further right now.

01:44:00.985 --> 01:44:04.988
So, until I make a call,
I'm going to go back to the office

01:44:05.072 --> 01:44:07.324
and see if there's anyone
in merchandising.

01:44:07.408 --> 01:44:11.244
Mary went back upstairs
and two hours later,

01:44:11.329 --> 01:44:15.665
she brought down this guy
whose job it is to buy the bullets for Kmart.

01:44:15.750 --> 01:44:18.335
-Stay out of trouble.
-Yes.

01:44:18.419 --> 01:44:20.754
We're not the ones in trouble, guys.

01:44:20.838 --> 01:44:23.214
Mark thought
he'd show him his bullet wounds.

01:44:23.299 --> 01:44:26.927
Those are his bullet holes
from your bullets.

01:44:27.011 --> 01:44:30.305
That's where the Kmart bullets went in.

01:44:30.389 --> 01:44:31.681
Well, take care.

01:44:31.766 --> 01:44:34.434
Is anybody else gonna come down?

01:44:34.518 --> 01:44:36.519
Is anybody else gonna come down?
Is that it?

01:44:36.604 --> 01:44:38.772
-Let me check.
-Okay. Thank you.

01:44:39.398 --> 01:44:43.693
We waited around a couple more hours,
but no one else came down.

01:44:43.778 --> 01:44:47.697
As we left the building,
Mark came up with an idea.

01:44:47.782 --> 01:44:52.577
He suggested that we go to the nearest Kmart
and buy out all their bullets.

01:44:54.789 --> 01:44:56.623
Just take as many of those as you can.

01:44:56.707 --> 01:44:59.125
You can come around here and look.

01:44:59.210 --> 01:45:01.628
What else do we have over here?

01:45:01.712 --> 01:45:04.881
You got .357s? Sure.
I'll take them all. Take everything you got.

01:45:05.508 --> 01:45:08.510
-So you're 17, and you're what?
-Sixteen.

01:45:08.594 --> 01:45:10.595
- Shit.
- Be careful.

01:45:10.680 --> 01:45:12.430
My God, Craig.

01:45:13.474 --> 01:45:16.726
Mark pretty much cleaned them out
of their ammunition.

01:45:16.811 --> 01:45:21.022
And the next day we decided to go back
to Kmart headquarters with all the bullets.

01:45:22.274 --> 01:45:24.818
This time we brought the press.

01:45:24.902 --> 01:45:28.655
Our local first coverage of southeastern
Michigan continues now with all-new stories.

01:45:28.739 --> 01:45:30.365
Coming up here in our 6:00 report,

01:45:30.449 --> 01:45:32.867
a warning to everyone this summer
to watch out for snakes.

01:45:32.952 --> 01:45:36.162
You'll hear from a mom
who was bitten by a rattlesnake.

01:45:36.247 --> 01:45:40.458
And also new, students who survived
the Columbine massacre are in town.

01:45:40.543 --> 01:45:42.377
They are very angry with Kmart.

01:45:42.461 --> 01:45:44.921
We're here to see Chuck Conaway,
the chairman of Kmart.

01:45:45.006 --> 01:45:46.673
- How you doing, sir?
- How you doing?

01:45:46.757 --> 01:45:49.759
It's always a pleasure to see you.
Okay. –

01:45:50.970 --> 01:45:53.388
They would like to speak with Mr. Conaway.

01:45:55.224 --> 01:45:57.851
Here's the nine millimeters.

01:45:57.935 --> 01:46:00.520
These are the bullets
that are in both Richard

01:46:00.604 --> 01:46:03.606
and in Mark's body right now.

01:46:04.525 --> 01:46:06.735
Want to take that?
I don't want to touch those.

01:46:06.819 --> 01:46:08.820
I will do that for you, sir.

01:46:10.948 --> 01:46:13.575
Move your group outside,
I'll have somebody here in five minutes.

01:46:13.659 --> 01:46:16.453
Do me a favor. Don't block the door.
Just off to the side, if you would.

01:46:16.537 --> 01:46:18.621
We'll go outside,
and somebody will come out.

01:46:18.706 --> 01:46:20.457
My name's Lori McTavish.

01:46:20.541 --> 01:46:23.293
I'm the vice president of communications
for Kmart.

01:46:23.377 --> 01:46:25.879
I'm happy to deliver a statement
on behalf of the company.

01:46:25.963 --> 01:46:29.549
What happened in Columbine, Colorado
was truly tragic

01:46:29.633 --> 01:46:31.551
and touched every American.

01:46:31.635 --> 01:46:36.097
And we're sorry for the disadvantage
to this young man.

01:46:36.182 --> 01:46:39.684
Kmart is phasing out the sale
of handgun ammunition.

01:46:39.769 --> 01:46:42.353
The business plan calls
for this to be complete

01:46:42.438 --> 01:46:46.524
in the continental US
within the next 90 days.

01:46:46.609 --> 01:46:49.277
-Wow!
-Kmart representatives met Mr. Moore

01:46:49.361 --> 01:46:52.572
and the students
from Columbine, Colorado yesterday

01:46:52.656 --> 01:46:54.657
and listened to their concerns

01:46:54.742 --> 01:46:57.702
about the product carried in Kmart stores.

01:46:57.787 --> 01:47:00.705
The company committed,
at the end of that meeting,

01:47:00.790 --> 01:47:04.292
that Kmart would have an answer for them
within a week's time.

01:47:04.376 --> 01:47:06.836
Well, the first thing we want to do
is thank you

01:47:06.921 --> 01:47:12.258
for committing to no longer selling
handgun ammunition in your stores

01:47:12.343 --> 01:47:13.718
and within 90 days.

01:47:13.803 --> 01:47:16.096
The process will be phased out
within 90 days.

01:47:16.180 --> 01:47:18.932
And after 90 days, there will be
no more selling of ammunition

01:47:19.016 --> 01:47:21.226
that can go into handguns
or assault weapons.

01:47:21.310 --> 01:47:25.271
Firearm ammunition will be –
We will not sell it after 90 days in our stores.

01:47:25.356 --> 01:47:27.732
-Well, we greatly appreciate that.
-Thank you.

01:47:27.817 --> 01:47:31.236
Thank you very much.
Thank you. This is very great.

01:47:33.656 --> 01:47:36.866
Thank you. Wow. That blows my mind.

01:47:36.951 --> 01:47:38.576
That's more than what we asked for.

01:47:38.661 --> 01:47:40.829
-This is remarkable.
-Yeah. Yeah.

01:47:40.913 --> 01:47:43.915
-Well, like I told you – Did you think?
-No.

01:47:43.999 --> 01:47:45.416
I'm, like – We're, like –

01:47:45.501 --> 01:47:47.502
We were just getting ready
to go to the air –

01:47:47.586 --> 01:47:49.629
-We were getting ready to go home.
-Go to the airport.

01:47:49.713 --> 01:47:49.754
The kids from Columbine had scored
an overwhelming victory against Kmart,

01:47:49.755 --> 01:47:53.758
The kids from Columbine had scored
an overwhelming victory against Kmart,

01:47:53.843 --> 01:47:57.637
and it inspired me to do something
that I knew I had to do.

01:47:58.722 --> 01:48:02.308
All I needed was a star map.

01:48:21.912 --> 01:48:23.788
-Hello?
-Mr. Heston?

01:48:23.873 --> 01:48:26.166
- Yeah.
-This is Michael Moore.

01:48:26.250 --> 01:48:27.500
- Yes.
-The filmmaker?

01:48:27.585 --> 01:48:29.586
-Yes, of course.
-Yes. How you doing?

01:48:29.670 --> 01:48:31.087
Fine, thank you.

01:48:31.172 --> 01:48:33.715
Listen, I was wondering
if maybe I could talk to you.

01:48:33.799 --> 01:48:37.969
We're making a documentary
about the whole gun issue,

01:48:38.053 --> 01:48:39.721
and I'm a member of the NRA.

01:48:39.805 --> 01:48:42.265
I thought maybe we could
talk a little bit about the –

01:48:42.349 --> 01:48:44.392
Tell you what. Let me look at my calendar.

01:48:44.476 --> 01:48:46.728
I may be able to give you
some time tomorrow.

01:48:46.812 --> 01:48:48.605
I have some people here now.

01:48:48.689 --> 01:48:50.732
How can I – Pardon me?

01:48:50.816 --> 01:48:52.317
- Hold the phone.
-Okay. Thank you.

01:48:52.401 --> 01:48:55.904
Okay. I can give you a little time
tomorrow morning.

01:48:55.988 --> 01:48:58.198
- I think that's Thursday.
-Yes.

01:48:58.282 --> 01:49:00.909
-Let's say 8:30.
-8:30 in the morning?

01:49:00.993 --> 01:49:02.994
Okay. And just come here?

01:49:03.078 --> 01:49:05.205
-Here. Yeah.
-Yes. Okay, good.

01:49:08.500 --> 01:49:10.585
--Hello?

01:49:10.669 --> 01:49:13.087
Hi. It's Michael Moore here
to see Charlton Heston.

01:49:13.172 --> 01:49:15.173
- Okay.

01:49:34.735 --> 01:49:36.236
Hi.

01:49:36.320 --> 01:49:37.820
Good morning.

01:49:42.034 --> 01:49:44.244
-How are you?
-Fine, thank you.

01:49:44.328 --> 01:49:46.788
Thank you very much
for agreeing to see me.

01:49:54.922 --> 01:49:57.340
He took me out
to his pool and tennis house

01:49:57.424 --> 01:49:59.801
so we could have a chat.

01:49:59.885 --> 01:50:02.470
I told him that I was a lifetime member
of the NRA

01:50:02.554 --> 01:50:04.806
and showed him my membership card.

01:50:04.890 --> 01:50:06.683
Good for you. Well done.

01:50:06.767 --> 01:50:09.769
-I assume you have guns in the house here?
-Indeed, I do.

01:50:09.853 --> 01:50:12.480
Bad guys, take notice.

01:50:12.564 --> 01:50:15.108
-So you have 'em for protection?
-Yeah. Sure.

01:50:15.192 --> 01:50:17.819
-Have you ever been a victim of crime?
-No. No.

01:50:17.903 --> 01:50:20.905
-Never – Yeah. Never been assaulted?
-No.

01:50:20.990 --> 01:50:23.992
No violence toward you,
but you have guns in the house.

01:50:24.076 --> 01:50:25.868
-Loaded.
-Loaded. They're loaded?

01:50:25.953 --> 01:50:29.956
Well, if you really need a weapon
for self-defense,

01:50:30.040 --> 01:50:31.791
you need it loaded.

01:50:31.875 --> 01:50:34.002
Okay, but why do you need it
for self-defense?

01:50:34.086 --> 01:50:34.961
I don't.

01:50:35.045 --> 01:50:37.588
You've never been a victim of crime.
You haven't been assaulted here.

01:50:37.673 --> 01:50:39.549
-That's true.
-Why would you –

01:50:39.633 --> 01:50:42.969
So why don't you unload the gun?

01:50:43.053 --> 01:50:47.557
Because, uh, the Second Amendment
gives me the right to have it loaded.

01:50:47.641 --> 01:50:49.851
I agree. I totally agree with that.

01:50:49.935 --> 01:50:52.603
But I'm just saying
the Second Amendment gives me –

01:50:52.688 --> 01:50:55.398
Let's say it's a comfort factor, you know?

01:50:55.482 --> 01:50:57.692
It gives you comfort to know
that there's a loaded gun?

01:50:57.776 --> 01:50:58.776
Yeah.

01:50:58.861 --> 01:51:01.446
Comfort, meaning it allows you
to relax and feel safe?

01:51:01.530 --> 01:51:03.865
-Not worry about it.
-Not worry, not be afraid.

01:51:03.949 --> 01:51:08.953
And I'm not really,
but I'm exercising one of the rights

01:51:09.038 --> 01:51:10.872
passed on down to me

01:51:10.956 --> 01:51:14.083
from those wise, old, dead, white guys
that invented this country.

01:51:14.168 --> 01:51:16.627
If it was good enough for them,
it's good enough for me.

01:51:16.712 --> 01:51:20.882
You could still exercise the right by having
the gun unloaded and locked away somewhere.

01:51:20.966 --> 01:51:22.258
I choose to have it.

01:51:22.343 --> 01:51:26.179
What sort of strikes me as interesting
is that in other countries,

01:51:26.263 --> 01:51:29.766
where they don't have the murder rate,
the gun murder rate that we have,

01:51:29.850 --> 01:51:33.353
that many people say that's because
they don't have guns around.

01:51:33.437 --> 01:51:37.231
It's hard to get a gun in Britain
or Germany or whatever.

01:51:37.316 --> 01:51:39.067
But we went to Canada,

01:51:39.151 --> 01:51:41.903
and there's seven million guns
in ten million homes.

01:51:41.987 --> 01:51:44.572
-There won't be very long.
-But hear me out though.

01:51:44.656 --> 01:51:46.449
Canada is a nation of hunters.

01:51:46.533 --> 01:51:51.412
Millions of guns, and yet they had
just a few murders last year.

01:51:51.497 --> 01:51:53.539
That's it.
Of a country of 30 million people.

01:51:53.624 --> 01:51:54.916
Here's my question.

01:51:55.000 --> 01:51:59.003
Why is it that they've got
all these guns laying around,

01:51:59.088 --> 01:52:02.590
yet they don't kill each other
at the level that we kill each other?

01:52:02.674 --> 01:52:08.513
I think American history
has a lot of blood on its hands.

01:52:08.597 --> 01:52:10.348
-And German history doesn't?
-No.

01:52:10.432 --> 01:52:13.226
-And British history?
-I don't think as much.

01:52:13.310 --> 01:52:16.396
Germans don't have
as much blood on their hands?

01:52:16.480 --> 01:52:18.064
-They do, yes.
-The Brits?

01:52:18.148 --> 01:52:21.359
They ruled the world for 300 years
at the barrel of a gun.

01:52:21.443 --> 01:52:25.113
They're all violent people.
They have bad guys, they have crime.

01:52:25.197 --> 01:52:27.782
They have lots of guns in the past.

01:52:27.866 --> 01:52:31.619
It's an interesting point
which can be explored,

01:52:31.703 --> 01:52:34.831
and you're good to explore it
at great length,

01:52:34.915 --> 01:52:37.917
but I think that's about all
I have to say on it.

01:52:38.001 --> 01:52:41.629
You don't have any opinion though
as to why we are the unique country,

01:52:41.713 --> 01:52:45.633
the only country that does this,
that kills each other on this level with guns?

01:52:45.717 --> 01:52:50.847
Well, we have probably
a more mixed ethnicity

01:52:50.931 --> 01:52:53.933
than other countries,
some other countries.

01:52:54.017 --> 01:52:55.685
You think it's an ethnic thing?

01:52:55.769 --> 01:52:58.604
No, I don't –
I wouldn't go so far as to say that.

01:52:58.689 --> 01:53:03.067
We had enough problems
with civil rights in the beginning.

01:53:03.152 --> 01:53:06.988
It's – But I have no answer for that.

01:53:07.072 --> 01:53:09.490
What do you mean,
you think it's a mixed ethnicity?

01:53:09.575 --> 01:53:11.325
I don't understand.

01:53:11.410 --> 01:53:16.914
-You said how is it so many Americans –
-That we're unique. Yeah.

01:53:16.999 --> 01:53:18.249
kill each other.

01:53:18.333 --> 01:53:21.127
I don't know that that's true, but even –

01:53:21.211 --> 01:53:24.422
No, you know that.
We have the highest murder rate with guns.

01:53:24.506 --> 01:53:26.466
It's way higher than any other country.

01:53:26.550 --> 01:53:29.010
The only answer I can give you
is the one I already gave you.

01:53:29.094 --> 01:53:30.428
Which is?

01:53:30.512 --> 01:53:35.975
Which is that we have a history of violence,

01:53:36.059 --> 01:53:38.603
perhaps more than most countries.

01:53:38.687 --> 01:53:41.230
Not more than Russia,
not more than Japan or China.

01:53:41.315 --> 01:53:43.983
-Not more than Germany.
-Not more than Germany.

01:53:44.067 --> 01:53:46.152
But certainly more than Canada.

01:53:47.154 --> 01:53:51.491
I come from Flint, Michigan,
and last year a little six-year-old boy

01:53:51.575 --> 01:53:55.453
took a gun into a classroom
and shot and killed a six-year-old girl.

01:53:55.537 --> 01:53:58.372
And it was really a tragic thing.

01:53:58.457 --> 01:54:01.542
-This was kids though. A kid?
-Yeah. Did you hear about this?

01:54:01.627 --> 01:54:03.628
-Yeah.
-A six-year-old shooting a six-year-old.

01:54:03.712 --> 01:54:06.714
-Yeah.
-Well, here's my question though.

01:54:06.798 --> 01:54:10.635
After that happened,
you came to Flint and held a big rally.

01:54:10.719 --> 01:54:12.053
Mm-hmm.

01:54:12.137 --> 01:54:16.849
-And, you know, I just –
-So did the vice president.

01:54:16.934 --> 01:54:19.936
Yeah, but did you feel
it was being at all insensitive

01:54:20.020 --> 01:54:22.104
to the fact that this community
had just gone through –

01:54:22.189 --> 01:54:24.690
Actually, I wasn't aware of that
at the time we came.

01:54:24.775 --> 01:54:28.945
We came and did an early morning rally

01:54:29.029 --> 01:54:31.197
and went onto wherever we were going.

01:54:31.281 --> 01:54:34.408
You didn't know at the time you were there
that this killing had happened?

01:54:34.493 --> 01:54:38.079
-Had you known, would you have not come?
-Would I have canceled?

01:54:38.163 --> 01:54:40.164
I don't –

01:54:40.249 --> 01:54:43.209
-It's hard to say.
-It wasn't like it was already planned.

01:54:43.293 --> 01:54:47.588
The choice to come there was made
after this horrible killing took place.

01:54:47.673 --> 01:54:48.839
Mm-hmm.

01:54:48.924 --> 01:54:51.801
Had you known that, would you have come?

01:54:51.885 --> 01:54:54.762
I don't know. I have no idea.

01:54:54.846 --> 01:54:57.807
-Maybe not? Maybe not.
-Okay. Thank you.

01:54:57.891 --> 01:55:01.143
You think you'd like to maybe apologize
to the people in Flint

01:55:01.228 --> 01:55:03.396
for coming and doing that at that time?

01:55:03.480 --> 01:55:07.275
You want me to apologize –
me to apologize to the people in Flint?

01:55:07.359 --> 01:55:10.778
Or the people in Columbine for coming
after their horrible tragedy?

01:55:10.862 --> 01:55:14.407
Why do you go to the places
after they have these horrible tragedies?

01:55:14.491 --> 01:55:16.826
I'm a member of your group here, and I'm –

01:55:16.910 --> 01:55:19.829
I'm afraid we don't agree on that.

01:55:19.913 --> 01:55:23.207
You think it's okay to just come
and show up at these events?

01:55:23.292 --> 01:55:24.959
No.

01:55:25.043 --> 01:55:27.044
You don't think it's okay?

01:55:37.889 --> 01:55:40.975
Mr. Heston, just one more thing.

01:55:41.059 --> 01:55:42.643
This is who she is.

01:55:42.728 --> 01:55:44.228
Or was.

01:55:45.480 --> 01:55:47.398
This is her. Please don't leave.

01:55:47.482 --> 01:55:50.234
Mr. Heston, please. Take a look at her.

01:55:50.319 --> 01:55:52.028
This is the girl.

01:56:45.040 --> 01:56:47.541
I left the Heston estate atop Beverly Hills

01:56:47.626 --> 01:56:49.502
and walked back into the real world,

01:56:49.586 --> 01:56:52.880
an America living and breathing in fear.

01:56:52.964 --> 01:56:55.091
In your mind you imagine somebody

01:56:55.175 --> 01:56:58.636
who might break into your house
to harm you or your family.

01:56:58.720 --> 01:57:01.222
What does that person look like?

01:57:01.306 --> 01:57:05.434
-You, her, him, the camera guy, anybody.
-Me? Her? Really?

01:57:05.519 --> 01:57:07.478
There could be a gun in the camera.
I don't know.

01:57:07.562 --> 01:57:09.689
Where gun sales
were now at an all-time high.

01:57:09.773 --> 01:57:12.942
You can shoot as fast
as with a semiautomatic.

01:57:13.026 --> 01:57:15.027
And where, in the end,

01:57:15.112 --> 01:57:18.447
it all comes back to bowling for Columbine.

01:57:18.532 --> 01:57:21.909
Three bowling alley employees
shot to death Sunday night

01:57:21.993 --> 01:57:23.452
at the AMF Broadway Lanes.

01:57:23.537 --> 01:57:26.664
There's nothing I really know.
I mean, I really don't know anything.

01:57:26.748 --> 01:57:30.710
Just that three people died
in Littleton in a bowling alley.

01:57:30.794 --> 01:57:32.336
I'm sorry.

01:57:32.421 --> 01:57:34.422
Have a nice day.

01:57:34.506 --> 01:57:37.842
Yes, it was a glorious time
to be an American.

